%md
## Load GS Data to HDFS
Loading the data directly to HDFS increases efficiency because the worker nodes in the file system are able to cache some of the data that was recently read from the disk. This makes subsequent requests run faster because they are obtaining data from the cache rather than the disk. 

This can be seen when I run the `SELECT COUNT(countryName) FROM wdi_csv_text` query from the `wdi_csv_table`. The first execution takes about 40 seconds, similar to the execution time on the `wdi_gs` table, but when I run the query a second time on `wdi_csv_table` it takes about 20 seconds since the data has already been cached.

%md
## Parsing Issue
Running a query to return a list of distinct indicatorcodes reveals a parsing issue with the table column since some of the values that are returning are clearly not indicator codes. A debug table is created to identify what exactly is causing the parsing issue which allows us to see that the column before the indicatorcode column contains strings which may have a comma within the string itself for that column. This caused the CSV parser to split up the rows incorrectly which resulted in the invalid indicatorcodes. To solve this issue a new Hive table was created using OpenCSVSerde on `GS` data and then exported the data to a hdfs location (using another Hive table). This solution fixed the parsing issue but when I ran the `SELECT COUNT(countryName)` on both the `wdi_csv_text` and the `wdi_opencsv_text` tables, the latter ran significantly slower. This is because SerDe requires more time to parse the rows so we trade off speed for more accuracy.

## OpenCSVSerde Limitation 
There is a limitation with OpenCSVSerde that effects the data type of table columns. This can be seen when we compare the table formats of `wdi_opencsv_text` and 'wdi_csv_text`. 

Some of the data types in `wdi_opencsv_text` are incorrect values for example the data type of indicatorvalue should be a float as seen in `wdi_cscv_text`. The reason for this is because SerDe treats all columns to be of type String. To convert the columns to the desired type I created a view over the table that does a CAST to the desired type.

%md
## Hive Partitions
We can optimize the previous query using the Hive partition feature. This feature is a way of dividing a table into related parts based on the values of partitioned columns such as date, city, and department. Using partition, it is easy to query a portion of the data. 

I used a dynamic partition which is designed to determine which partitions should be created and populated while scanning the input table. The table is partitioned based of the year column of the table which creates a directory for each distinct value of year, and storing all rows with that year value in that directory. When compared with the previous query, the execution time using partitions is much faster since it only needs to search the 2015 year directory.

## Columnar File Optimization 
We can also optimize the HQL query by storing the data in columnar format like parquet. Columnar formats enable greater efficiency, in both file size and query performance. File sizes are usually smaller than row-oriented equivalents since in a columnar format the values from one column are stored next to each other, which usually allows a very efficient encoding. Query performance is improved too since a query engine can skip over columns that are not needed to answer a query. 

When comparing that Canada 2015 GDP query, it is much faster in the `wdi_csv_parquet` table since it utilizes this columnar parquet format.

Below you can find a query that will find the highest GDP groeht value for each country. The query runs faster with the Spark that it did with Hive, because the operations are being performed in main memory.

paragraphs.text:
SELECT A.indicatorvalue AS GDP_growth_value, A.year AS Year, A.countryname AS countryName
FROM wdi_csv_parquet A  
INNER JOIN (SELECT MAX(indicatorvalue) AS indicatorvalue, countryname
    FROM wdi_csv_parquet
    WHERE indicatorcode="NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG"
    GROUP BY countryname) B
WHERE A.countryname = B.countryname AND A.indicatorvalue = B.indicatorvalue AND indicatorcode="NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG"

SELECT A.indicatorvalue AS GDP_growth_value, A.year AS Year, A.countryname AS countryName
FROM wdi_csv_parquet A  
INNER JOIN (SELECT MAX(indicatorvalue) AS indicatorvalue, countryname
    FROM wdi_csv_parquet
    WHERE indicatorcode="NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG"
    GROUP BY countryname) B
WHERE A.countryname = B.countryname AND A.indicatorvalue = B.indicatorvalue AND indicatorcode="NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG"
